# Example vault env template — copied to your project root on `dockpipe init` as `.env.vault.template.example`.
#
# 1Password CLI (`op`) is installable separately: https://developer.1password.com/docs/cli/
#
# If you prefer no vendor CLI, use the bundled `secretstore` workflow + `dotenv` resolver with a plain
# `.env.secretstore` file instead — see `src/core/workflows/secretstore/README.md`.
#
# Next steps for op inject:
#   1. Copy this file to `.env.vault.template` (gitignored) and edit `op://` lines for your vault items.
#   2. Ensure `dockpipe.config.json` sets `secrets.vault_template` (default init seeds `.env.vault.template`).
#   3. Set `secrets.vault` to `op` or add `vault: op` on workflows — DockPipe runs `op inject` before steps.
#
# Tool profiles (Codex, VS Code, …) live under `templates/core/resolvers/` after init. Install optional
# resolver packages with `dockpipe install package …` when your DockPipe release or registry ships them.
#
# Do not write partial op:// references inside comments — op inject scans the whole file.
#
# 1Password (op://) example — Vault: DockPipe | Item: CLOUDFLARE (fields: url, token, accesskeyid, secretaccesskey)

CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=op://DockPipe/CLOUDFLARE/token
CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID=op://DockPipe/CLOUDFLARE/url

R2_BUCKET=your-r2-bucket-name

AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=op://DockPipe/CLOUDFLARE/accesskeyid
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=op://DockPipe/CLOUDFLARE/secretaccesskey
R2_STATE_ACCESS_KEY_ID=op://DockPipe/CLOUDFLARE/accesskeyid
R2_STATE_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=op://DockPipe/CLOUDFLARE/secretaccesskey
